var questions_udemy3 = [{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-1","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following securities acts covers the registration and disclosure requirements of new issues?","choices":{"A":"The Securities Act of 1933","B":"The Securities Exchange Act of 1934","C":"The Trust Indenture Act of 1939","D":"All of the above"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A. the Securities Act of 1933\nThe Securities Act of 1933 covers the sale of new issues (primary market). The Securities Act of 1933 was designed to provide more transparency in financial statements and to curb fraudulent activities of issuers. The Securities Act of 1933 also goes by a myriad of other names, such as the Paper Act, New Issues Act, Full Disclosure Act, and Truth in Securities Act.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-2","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"One of your clients is interested in purchasing municipal general obligation (GO) bonds and asks for guidance. Which of the following statements are true?\nI. GO bond interest is subject to federal income tax.\nII. GO bonds are backed by the full faith, credit, and taxing power of the municipality.\nIII. GO bond issues generally require voter approval.\nIV. GO bond proceeds typically fund non-revenue-producing facilities such as schools and roads.","choices":{"A":"I and II","B":"II, III, and IV","C":"I, III, and IV","D":"I, II, and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"GO bonds are backed by the municipality's taxing power (II), normally require voter approval (III), and fund non-revenue-producing projects (IV). Their interest is generally exempt from federal income tax, so I is false.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-3","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Corporations that sell bonds are taking the position of a(n)","choices":{"A":"borrower","B":"loan shark","C":"investment banker","D":"creditor"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Issuers of bonds are borrowing money from investors.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-4","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"All of the following would violate the political contributions rule (MSRB Rule G-37) EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"$100 contribution to a candidate for whom a municipal finance professional (MFP) may vote","B":"$100 contribution to a candidate for whom a municipal finance professional (MFP) may not vote","C":"$400 contribution to a candidate for whom a municipal finance professional (MFP) may vote","D":"$400 contribution to a candidate for whom a municipal finance professional (MFP) may not vote"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A. $100 contribution to a candidate for whom a municipal finance professional (MFP) may vote\nMunicipal finance professionals are allowed to make political contributions for up to $250 per election per candidate for whom they're allowed to vote. They're not allowed to make political contributions for individuals they're not allowed to vote for.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-5","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"All of the following are governed by MSRB rules EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"issuers","B":"registered reps","C":"broker-dealers","D":"bank-dealers"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board (MSRB) establishes rules that broker-dealers, bank-dealers, and municipal advisors must follow when engaging in transactions of municipal securities. Issuers aren't subject to MSRB rules.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-6","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"For an investment company to be considered diversified, what is the maximum percentage of outstanding shares that the investment company can own of another company?","choices":{"A":"1%","B":"5%","C":"10%","D":"15%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"C. 10% According to the Investment Company Act of 1940, out of the 75% that must be diversified, a diversified investment company may not own more than 10% of outstanding shares of another company. In addition, the investment company cannot invest more than 5% of its diversified assets into one issuer's securities.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-7","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which two of the following corporate characteristics are the easiest for a limited partnership to avoid?\nI. Having perpetual life\nII. Providing limited liability\nIII. Having centralized management\nIV. Having free transferability","choices":{"A":"I and III","B":"I and IV","C":"II and III","D":"II and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To avoid being taxed as a corporation, a partnership must avoid at least two corporate characteristics. The easiest to avoid are perpetual life (partnerships are for a finite period) and free transferability of interest.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-8","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Unless otherwise stated, a stock option contract represents","choices":{"A":"1 share of the underlying security","B":"10 shares of the underlying security","C":"100 shares of the underlying security","D":"1,000 shares of the underlying security"},"answer":"C","explanation":"C. 100 shares of the underlying security. Most option contracts represent 100 shares of the underlying security.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-9","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following must be verified when opening an account for a new client?\nI. Citizenship\nII. Whether or not their name appears on the SDN list\nIII. Whether they work at another broker-dealer or not\nIV. Whether they have any accounts at another broker-dealer","choices":{"A":"I and IV","B":"II and III","C":"I, II, and III","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"You need to know citizenship, SDN-list status, and whether the customer works for another broker-dealer. Knowing of other brokerage accounts is helpful but not required.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-10","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following securities is subject to the LEAST market risk?","choices":{"A":"GNMA","B":"AAA rated GO bonds","C":"AAA rated corporate bonds","D":"Bond anticipation notes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Market risk is the risk that the price of a security will decline due to negative market conditions. Because bond anticipation notes (BANs) are short term, they're not in the market as long and, therefore, are less subject to market risk.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-11","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"All of the following trades occur in the secondary market EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"a syndicate selling new issues of municipal GO bonds to the public","B":"a designated market maker purchasing common stock for their own account","C":"a corporation selling its shares of treasury stock to the public using the services of a broker-dealer","D":"a trade between an insurance company and a bank without using the services of a broker-dealer"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A. a syndicate selling new issues of municipal GO bonds to the public\nRemember, new issues are always sold in the primary market regardless of whether they're municipal GO bonds or any other security. By contrast, sales of outstanding securities or previously outstanding securities (treasury stock) always take place in the secondary market. The secondary market is broken down into the following: First market: Listed securities trading on an exchange; Second market: Unlisted securities trading over-the-counter; Third market: Listed securities trading over-the-counter; Fourth market: Institutional trading without using the services of a broker-dealer.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-12","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"All of the following taxes are progressive EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"personal income","B":"gift","C":"estate","D":"sales"},"answer":"D","explanation":"D. sales Progressive taxes are taxes that increase depending on an individual's tax bracket. Progressive taxes affect individuals with high incomes more than individuals with low incomes. Personal income, gift, and estate taxes are progressive taxes. Sales tax and excise taxes (gas, alcohol, tobacco, and so on) are regressive taxes because everyone is taxed at the same rate.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-13","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) regulates the trading of which of the following?\nI. Common stock.\nII. Commodity futures contracts.\nIII. Corporate bonds.\nIV. Options on listed stocks.","choices":{"A":"I, III, and IV","B":"I, II, and III","C":"II, III, and IV","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The SEC regulates trading in securities—common stock (I), corporate bonds (III), and listed stock options (IV). Commodity futures are regulated by the CFTC, not the SEC, so II is excluded.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-14","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"The Securities Act of 1933 was enacted to","choices":{"A":"require full and fair disclosure regarding sales of new securities to the public","B":"regulate the exchanges and the over-the-counter market in trades of outstanding securities","C":"require broker-dealers and registered reps to be licensed","D":"all of the above"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The main purpose of the Securities Act of 1933 is to require the full and fair disclosure regarding sales of new securities to the public.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-15","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Equity securities include","choices":{"A":"TIPS","B":"debentures","C":"preferred shares","D":"GO bonds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Common and preferred stock are both equity securities which represent ownership of the issuing corporation. TIPS, debentures, and GO bonds are debt securities.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-16","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"An investor who purchases a corporate bond is:\nI. purchasing an ownership interest in the corporation.\nII. lending money to the corporation.\nIII. becoming a creditor of the corporation.\nIV. acquiring a claim on assets that is subordinate to the common shareholders.","choices":{"A":"I and II","B":"I and IV","C":"II and III","D":"III and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A bondholder lends money to the issuer (II) and takes the position of a creditor (III). Bondholders do not own the company (I is false) and are senior to shareholders, not subordinate (IV is false).","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-17","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Where did the tax-free reciprocal rule for municipal bonds and U.S. government securities originate from?","choices":{"A":"The IRS","B":"FINRA","C":"The Supreme Court","D":"The SEC"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Supreme Court established regulations that made interest payments on municipal bonds federally tax-free and interest payments on U.S. government bonds state tax-free.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-18","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Under the Investment Company Act of 1940, which of the following would be unlawful regarding the use of a mutual fund prospectus?","choices":{"A":"Using a prospectus to help elicit a sale","B":"Sending a prospectus to someone who didn't ask for it","C":"Not reading over the prospectus yourself prior to sending it out to a potential customer","D":"Circling or highlighting a particular section of the prospectus"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Whether the prospectus is for a mutual fund or any other security, you may not alter it in any way, even if the customer asks you to.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-19","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"Marge is a 54-year-old investor from Utah who is looking to add some liquidity to her portfolio. All of the following investments would help Marge meet that goal EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"an aggressive growth fund","B":"an oil and gas limited partnership","C":"blue-chip stocks","D":"Treasury bills"},"answer":"B","explanation":"B. an oil and gas limited partnership\nIf Marge is looking to add some liquidity (ease of trading) to her portfolio, an oil and gas limited partnership would not make sense. Limited partnerships (DPPs) are some of the most difficult investments to get in and out of. Limited partnerships require not only approval of the registered rep but also require approval of the general partner of the limited partnership. Limited partnership investors not only need a certain minimum deposit, but would also need to have liquidity in other investments in case the limited partnership needs additional funds to meet its goal.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-20","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"An ABC call option premium increased by .65. What is the dollar amount of the increase?","choices":{"A":"$0.65","B":"$6.50","C":"$65","D":"$650"},"answer":"C","explanation":"This is a fairly easy question if you remember that options are for 100 shares unless otherwise stated in the question. It's as simple as taking the premium increase and multiplying it by 100. 0.65 x 100 = $65","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-21","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"All of the following information must be obtained from a new individual customer EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"the individual's Social Security number","B":"the individual's date of birth","C":"the individual's educational background","D":"the individual's residential address"},"answer":"C","explanation":"C. the individual's educational background The individual's Social Security number, date of birth, and residential address are all required from a customer when opening an account. Although the individual's educational background would be helpful to have, it's not required.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-22","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"One of your clients is interested in purchasing the common stock from several companies based in Europe. As their registered representative, you should explain to them the risks of investing in these securities. The risks include: I. political risk II. market risk III. currency risk IV. interest rate risk","choices":{"A":"I and III","B":"I, III, and IV","C":"I, II, and III","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The client would face political (legislative) risk, market risk, and currency risk but not interest rate risk because they aren't buying fixed income securities.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-23","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The first time a corporation ever sells securities is called a(n)","choices":{"A":"primary offering","B":"first market trade","C":"opening transaction","D":"initial public offering"},"answer":"D","explanation":"D. initial public offering\nAn initial public offering (IPO) is the first time a corporation over sells stock to the public.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-24","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Which of the following taxes are regressive?\nI. Federal income tax.\nII. General sales tax.\nIII. Gasoline (excise) tax.\nIV. Alcohol tax.","choices":{"A":"I, II, and III","B":"I and IV","C":"II, III, and IV","D":"I, III, and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Regressive taxes take the same rate from everyone regardless of income—sales, gasoline, and alcohol (excise) taxes (II, III, IV). The federal income tax is progressive, so I is excluded.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-25","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The federal security law that provides rules for securities traded in the secondary market is","choices":{"A":"the Trust Indenture Act of 1939","B":"the Securities Exchange Act of 1934","C":"the Securities Act of 1933","D":"FDIC"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Securities Exchange Act of 1934 was designed to provide rules for the trading of outstanding securities in the over-the-counter (OTC) market and on exchanges.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-26","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Regarding investments, which of the following is true?","choices":{"A":"Bonds represent ownership in an issuing corporation.","B":"Warrants and bonds represent ownership in an issuing corporation.","C":"Stocks represent ownership in an issuing corporation.","D":"Warrants represent ownership in an issuing corporation."},"answer":"C","explanation":"C. Stocks represent ownership in an issuing corporation. Stocks are equity securities that represent ownership in the issuing corporation. Bonds are debt securities that represent a loan to the issuer. Warrants are long-term marketable securities that give the holder the right to purchase stock of the issuer at a fixed price.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-27","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Dee Plump, an investor, owns a TUIB 5% convertible bond purchased at 103 with five years until maturity. If they hold the bond until maturity, Dee will receive","choices":{"A":"$970","B":"$1,000","C":"$1,015","D":"$1,030"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When holding a bond until maturity, an investor will receive par value. Assume par value is $1,000 unless stated differently in the question.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-28","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"One of your clients is interested in purchasing municipal GO bonds and is looking for guidance. You can inform him that: I. they are issued to fund revenue-producing facilities II. they are backed by the taxing power of the municipality III. they need approval of voters to be issued IV. they are subject to a debt ceiling","choices":{"A":"I and IV","B":"II, III, and IV","C":"II and III","D":"I, III, and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"General obligation (GO) bonds are issued to fund non-revenue-producing facilities and are backed by the taxing power of the municipality. Because residents pay additional taxes to back the bonds, they need voter approval. Also, GO bonds are subject to a debt ceiling.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-29","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Mutual fund redemptions must be completed within","choices":{"A":"5 days","B":"5 business days","C":"7 days","D":"7 business days"},"answer":"C","explanation":"C. 7 days\nMutual fund redemption must be completed within 7 calendar days.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-30","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"All of the following are true regarding limited partners EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"they have access to unlimited financial information regarding the partnership","B":"they may participate in management decisions since they have a tremendous amount of risk","C":"they may vote to terminate a partnership","D":"they may invest in competing partnerships"},"answer":"B","explanation":"B. they may participate in management decisions since they have a tremendous amount of risk The general partner(s) make the management decisions, not the limited partners.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-31","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Standard option contracts are issued with an expiration of","choices":{"A":"6 months","B":"9 months","C":"12 months","D":"39 months"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Standard option contracts are issued with 9-month expirations. Long-term equity anticipation securities (LEAPS) may have expirations of up to 39 months.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-32","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"A client's nonfinancial considerations are typically as important as their financial considerations. Nonfinancial considerations include","choices":{"A":"the client's age","B":"the client's marital status","C":"the client's employment status","D":"all of the above"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When opening an account for a client, you should help determine the risk tolerance and investment goals. Part of that includes looking at the client's financial and nonfinancial considerations. Some of the nonfinancial considerations are the customer's age, marital status, number of dependents, employment status, and employment of other family members.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-33","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"One of your customers wants to invest in a retirement plan that protects against purchasing power risk. Which of the following would be the most suitable investment?","choices":{"A":"Corporate bonds","B":"Preferred stock","C":"Variable annuities","D":"Fixed annuities"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Purchasing power risk is inflation risk. Variable annuities provide variable payouts while fixed annuities provide fixed payouts. A fixed annuity's guaranteed payments are worth less over time; a variable annuity gives investors the potential to outperform the inflation rate.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-34","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"A corporation was authorized to sell 50 million shares to the public. In the initial public offering, they only sold 30 million shares. One year later, they now want to sell another 5 million shares. The 5 million shares being sold would be a","choices":{"A":"primary offering","B":"first market trade","C":"secondary offering","D":"second market trade"},"answer":"A","explanation":"C. Variable annuities Purchasing power risk is inflation risk. Variable annuities provide variable payouts while fixed annuities provide fixed payouts. If anyone invests in a fixed annuity, although the fixed payouts are guaranteed, the money received is worth less as time goes on. A variable annuity gives investors the potential to outperform the inflation rate.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-36","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"Which of the following securities acts created the Securities and Exchange Commission?","choices":{"A":"The Securities Act of 1933","B":"The Securities and Exchange Act of 1934","C":"The Trust Indenture Act of 1939","D":"The Investment Company Act of 1940"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Securities and Exchange Act of 1934 created the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC).","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-37","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The Securities Exchange Act of 1934 created rules regarding all of the following EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"the extension of credit in margin accounts","B":"transactions by insiders","C":"(not captured - registration of new securities, governed by the 1933 Act)","D":"(not captured)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Securities Exchange Act of 1934 covers margin credit, insider trading, exchanges and OTC markets; registration of new issues is handled by the Securities Act of 1933, so that is the EXCEPT answer.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-38","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"AylDec Corporation has just decided to go public. AylDec will issue","choices":{"A":"preferred stock","B":"common stock","C":"term bonds","D":"warrants"},"answer":"B","explanation":"B. common stock\nAll public corporations issue common stock. They may also issue bonds, preferred stock, and warrants, but they don't have to.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-39","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"ABC Corporate Bonds are quoted at 101 1/8. How much would an investor purchasing ten of these bonds pay?","choices":{"A":"$1,013.75","B":"$1,013.80","C":"$10,137.50","D":"$10,138.00"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Convert the fraction to a decimal: 101 1/8 = 101.125. Bonds are a percentage of $1,000 par, so 101.125% x $1,000 = $1,011.25 each. For ten bonds: $1,011.25 x 10 = $10,112.50. NOTE: the captured explanation text referenced 101 3/8 ($10,137.50) which corresponds to a slightly different quote; the correct math for 101 1/8 yields $10,112.50, but the exam key recorded in the source frames is C ($10,137.50) for the 101 3/8 version. Verify quote in source.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-40","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following municipal securities is backed by the full faith and credit of the issuer? (I. General Obligation, II. Revenue, III. Double-barreled, IV. Moral obligation)","choices":{"A":"I and II","B":"I and III","C":"II and IV","D":"I, III, and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"General obligation (GO) bonds and double-barreled bonds are backed by the full faith and credit and taxing power of the municipal issuer. Double-barreled bonds are also backed by a revenue-producing facility, and if those revenues are insufficient to pay principal and interest, they are backed by the municipality.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-41","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The custodian bank for a mutual fund","choices":{"A":"provides security in the event of corporate bankruptcy of one of the securities held by the fund","B":"is responsible for the safekeeping of the fund's cash and securities","C":"provides loans for investors purchasing securities on margin","D":"redeems investor shares"},"answer":"B","explanation":"B. is responsible for the safekeeping of the fund's cash and securities. The custodian bank of a mutual fund is responsible for the safekeeping of the fund's cash and securities.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-42","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"Which of the following is fiduciarily responsible regarding a limited partnership?","choices":{"A":"General partners","B":"Limited partners","C":"Both A. and B.","D":"Neither A. nor B."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The limited partners are the main investors of a limited partnership. The general partner(s) have the fiduciary responsibility to run the partnership to the best of their ability.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-43","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Bullish option strategies include  I. buying calls  II. buying puts  III. writing in-the-money calls  IV. writing in-the-money puts","choices":{"A":"I and III","B":"I and IV","C":"II and III","D":"II and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Buying calls is bullish (want the underlying to rise). Writing in-the-money puts is also bullish: the seller wants the stock price to stay above the strike so the put expires worthless and they keep the premium.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-44","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"If holding which of the following positions would an investor deliver the stock if exercised?","choices":{"A":"Long a call or short a call","B":"Long a call or short a put","C":"Long a put or short a call","D":"Long a put or short a put"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Investors who are long a put or short a call would deliver a stock when the option is exercised. Long a call - the right to buy the stock. Long a put - the right to sell the stock. Short a call - the obligation to sell the stock. Short a put - the obligation to buy the stock.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-45","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"You are in the process of opening a new customer account. Which of the following information do you need? (I. Social Security number or tax ID  II. Educational background  III. Age and marital status  IV. Occupation and employer)","choices":{"A":"I and IV","B":"I, II, and IV","C":"I, III, and IV","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Statements I and IV were probably a given. But you also need the type of account that the customer is opening (cash, margin, corporate, and so on), the customer's age and marital status, and the customer's occupation and employer. You don't need the customer's educational background.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-46","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Zero coupon bonds have no ________ risk.","choices":{"A":"reinvestment","B":"purchasing power","C":"market","D":"interest"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Reinvestment risk is the additional risk taken with interest or dividends received. Since zero-coupon bonds make no interest payments (they are issued at a discount and mature at par value), there is nothing to reinvest.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-47","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following describe the secondary market? (I. The trading for OTC issues  II. The trading of listed securities  III. The trading of outstanding issues  IV. The underwriting of new issues)","choices":{"A":"I and III","B":"II and IV","C":"I, II, and III","D":"I, II, and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The secondary market is where outstanding (already-issued) securities trade. It includes OTC trading (I) and listed securities trading (II), as well as trading of outstanding issues (III). The underwriting of new issues (IV) is the primary market, not the secondary market. NOTE: no dedicated explanation paragraph appeared on this frame; the overflow text visible was the zero-coupon-bonds reinvestment explanation from Q46.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-48","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Earned income includes all of the following EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"capital gains","B":"salary","C":"bonuses","D":"income received from active participation in a business"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Earned (active) income includes salaries, bonuses, and any income received from active participation in a business. Capital gains are considered portfolio income.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-49","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"What is the primary purpose of self-regulatory organizations such as FINRA?","choices":{"A":"To register and create a market for new securities","B":"To prosecute people for insider trading activities","C":"To help promote fair and equitable practices among its members","D":"To insure investors in the event of broker-dealer bankruptcy"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Self-regulatory organizations (SROs) such as FINRA, MSRB, NYSE, and so on, make sure there are fair and equitable practices among their members.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-50","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following securities is exempt from the Trust Indenture Act of 1939? (I. T-bonds  II. GO bonds  III. Equipment trust bonds  IV. Revenue bonds)","choices":{"A":"I only","B":"II and III","C":"I, II, and IV","D":"I, III, and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Trust Indenture Act of 1939 regulates all corporate bond issues exceeding $5 million. The only corporate bonds listed are equipment trust bonds. U.S. government T-bonds, municipal general obligation (GO) bonds, and municipal revenue bonds are exempt from the Trust Indenture Act of 1939.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-51","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Poor Outlook Corporation has just declared bankruptcy. Remaining assets would be distributed in which way (from first to last)?","choices":{"A":"IRS, unpaid workers, general creditors, preferred stockholders, secured creditors, subordinated debenture holders, common stockholders","B":"Common stockholders, general creditors, preferred stockholders, subordinated debenture holders, secured creditors, IRS, unpaid workers","C":"Unpaid workers, IRS, secured creditors, general creditors, subordinated debenture holders, preferred stockholders, common stockholders","D":"IRS, unpaid workers, secured creditors, subordinated debenture holders, general creditors, preferred stockholders, common stockholders"},"answer":"C","explanation":"C. Unpaid workers, IRS, secured creditors, general creditors, subordinated debenture holders, preferred stockholders, common stockholders. In the event that a corporation declares bankruptcy, the corporate assets are distributed in the following way: unpaid workers, IRS, secured creditors, general creditors, subordinated debenture holders, preferred stockholders, and finally (if there's anything left) common stockholders.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-52","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which is the only yield found on the indenture of a bond?","choices":{"A":"Nominal yield","B":"Current yield","C":"Yield to maturity","D":"Yield to call"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A. Nominal yield. The only yield found on the indenture of a bond is the nominal yield or coupon rate. The reason the other yields can't be on the indenture of a bond is because they change as the market price changes.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-53","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Municipal bonds can be issued by (I. local governments  II. states  III. the U.S. government  IV. Corporations)","choices":{"A":"I only","B":"I and II","C":"I, II, and III","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Municipal bonds are debt securities issued by state and local governments (including cities, counties, and school districts) to fund public projects. The U.S. government issues Treasury securities, not municipal bonds. Corporations issue corporate bonds. Therefore, only local governments (I) and states (II) are issuers of municipal bonds.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-54","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following is true regarding Rule 17a-6?","choices":{"A":"Affiliated persons of an investment company are not allowed to trade the fund's portfolio of securities and are not allowed to buy or redeem shares of the fund.","B":"Affiliated persons of an investment company are not allowed to trade the fund's portfolio of securities but are allowed to buy or redeem shares of the fund.","C":"Affiliated persons of an investment company are allowed to trade the fund's portfolio of securities but are not allowed to buy or redeem shares of the fund.","D":"Affiliated persons of an investment company are allowed to trade the fund's portfolio of securities and are allowed to buy or redeem shares of the fund."},"answer":"B","explanation":"B. Affiliated persons of an investment company are not allowed to trade the fund's portfolio of securities but are allowed to buy or redeem shares of the fund. Affiliated persons of investment companies (persons affiliated with the manager of the fund, the custodian bank, and owners of 5% or more of the outstanding shares of the fund) are not allowed to trade securities within the fund's portfolio of securities. However, affiliated persons are certainly allowed to buy and redeem shares of the fund like regular public customers.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-55","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Which of the following is true of limited partnerships?","choices":{"A":"They have perpetual life.","B":"They must end on a predetermined date.","C":"They may end by vote.","D":"They must end on a predetermined date and by vote."},"answer":"D","explanation":"They must end on a predetermined date or end by vote. Unlike corporations that are formed with the idea of having a perpetual life, limited partnerships are set up for a predetermined date or goal. The only way they can dissolve the partnership prior to that is by a vote of the limited partners.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-56","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"An investor owns 100 shares of DIM common stock. Which of the following would provide this investor a full hedge for this position?","choices":{"A":"Long a DIM call","B":"Long a DIM put","C":"Short a DIM call","D":"Short a DIM put"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The best hedge (protection) for an investor who owns stock is to purchase a put option on the same security at the current market price or higher. If the stock price declines, the investor can exercise the put and sell the stock at the strike price.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-57","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following needs to be filled out on a new account form? (I. The customer's name and address  II. The customer's date of birth  III. The type of account  IV. The customer's investment objectives)","choices":{"A":"I and II","B":"I, II, and III","C":"I, II, and IV","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When opening a new account, financial firms are required to collect comprehensive information to comply with 'Know Your Customer' (KYC) and anti-money laundering (AML) regulations, as well as to ensure investment suitability. The customer's name and address (I) and date of birth (II) are required for identification and verification. The type of account (III) establishes the legal structure (e.g., individual, joint, IRA). Finally, the customer's investment objectives (IV) are necessary to determine the suitability of future investment recommendations, ensuring they align with the client's risk tolerance and financial goals.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-58","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Investors who have international investments are subject to ________ risk.","choices":{"A":"political","B":"currency","C":"exchange-rate","D":"country"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Investors with international investments are exposed to currency risk (also called exchange-rate risk) — the risk that fluctuations in foreign currency values will affect the value of their investment when converted back to their home currency.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-59","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which TWO of the following are true regarding primary and secondary distributions? (I. Primary distributions are involved in the sale of new shares by the issuing corporation.  II. Primary distributions are involved in the sale of previously issued and outstanding shares.  III. Secondary distributions are involved in the sale of new shares by the issuing corporation.  IV. Secondary distributions are involved in the sale of previously issued and outstanding shares.)","choices":{"A":"I and III","B":"I and IV","C":"II and III","D":"II and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Primary distributions are the selling of new shares being sold by the issuer. Secondary distributions involve the sale of shares that have already been issued and outstanding shares.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-60","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following are included in portfolio income? (I. income from an oil and gas DPP  II. income from stock dividends  III. interest from corporate bonds  IV. capital gains from the sale of municipal bonds)","choices":{"A":"I, II, and III","B":"II, III, and IV","C":"II and III","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Portfolio income includes net capital gains from the sale of securities (including municipal bonds), dividends, and interest. Income, gains, and losses from a DPP (direct participation program) are passive.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-61","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following is NOT TRUE of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934?","choices":{"A":"It regulates the extension of credit.","B":"It regulates trades of securities in the primary market.","C":"It regulates trades of securities in the OTC market.","D":"It regulates trades of securities in the exchange market."},"answer":"B","explanation":"B. It regulates trades of securities in the primary market. The Securities Act of 1933 regulates trading of securities in the primary (new issue) market. The Securities Exchange Act of 1934 regulates trades of outstanding securities in the secondary market.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-62","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The Trust Indenture Act of 1939 regulates all of the following EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"debentures","B":"collateral trusts","C":"mortgage bonds","D":"Treasury bonds"},"answer":"D","explanation":"D. Treasury bonds. The Trust Indenture Act of 1939 regulates all corporate bond issues exceeding $5 million. Since Treasury bonds are issued by the U.S. government, they are exempt from the Trust Indenture Act of 1939.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-63","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"In the event of corporate bankruptcy, preferred stockholders have priority claim of assets over","choices":{"A":"unpaid workers","B":"debenture holders","C":"the IRS","D":"common shareholders"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the event of a corporate bankruptcy, common stockholders have a residual claim on assets, meaning that they are the last to get paid if there are any assets left.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-64","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"An investor owns ten 6% corporate bonds purchased at 102 with 7 years until maturity. If holding the bonds until maturity, the investor would receive?","choices":{"A":"$10,000","B":"$10,200","C":"$10,000 plus $300 interest","D":"$10,000 plus $600 interest"},"answer":"C","explanation":"At maturity the investor receives par: 10 bonds x $1,000 = $10,000, plus the final semiannual interest payment of 6% / 2 x $10,000 = $300.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-65","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following is NOT a source of funding for municipal revenue bonds?","choices":{"A":"Airports","B":"Tolls","C":"Property taxes","D":"User fees"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Property taxes (ad valorem taxes) are the largest source of funding for municipal general obligation (GO) bonds, not revenue bonds. Revenue bonds are repaid from the revenues of the project they finance (e.g., airports, tolls, user fees).","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-66","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"For mutual funds, what is the limit on the quantity of shares that can be sold to investors?","choices":{"A":"There is no limit.","B":"The limit depends on the type of mutual fund.","C":"The limit is determined by the SEC.","D":"The limit is determined by the fund's board of directors."},"answer":"A","explanation":"There is no limit on the number of mutual fund shares that can be sold to investors (open-end funds continually issue and redeem shares based on net asset value).","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-67","section":"3 - Trading, Accounts & Prohibited","stem":"Place in order from first to last how the remaining assets are distributed upon the dissolution of a limited partnership. (I. creditors  II. limited partners return of capital  III. general partners return of capital  IV. limited partners share of profits)","choices":{"A":"IV, II, I, III","B":"I, II, IV, III","C":"II, IV, I, III","D":"I, III, II, IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Upon dissolution of a limited partnership, assets are distributed in this order: (1) return of capital to limited partners, (2) limited partners' share of profits, (3) creditors, (4) return of capital to general partners.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-68","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Bearish option positions are","choices":{"A":"writers of puts and writers of calls","B":"buyers of puts and buyers of calls","C":"writers of puts and buyers of calls","D":"buyers of puts and writers of calls"},"answer":"D","explanation":"D. buyers of puts and writers of calls. If someone is bearish on a particular security, they want the price to decrease. With no other positions in the underlying stock, both buyers of puts and writers of calls want the price of the underlying stock to decrease.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-69","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"As part of the USA Patriot Act of 2001, all financial institutions must maintain","choices":{"A":"customer identification programs","B":"a fidelity bond","C":"SIPC coverage","D":"all of the above"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A. customer identification programs. Under the USA Patriot Act, all financial institutions must maintain customer identification programs (CIPs). It's up to the financial institution to verify the identity of any new customers, maintain records of how they verified the identity, and determine whether the new customer appears on any suspected terrorist list or terrorism organization. As part of the identification program, they must obtain the customer's name, date of birth, address (no P.O. boxes), and Social Security number.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-70","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Which of the following is the risk of not being able to sell a security quickly if needed?","choices":{"A":"Reinvestment risk","B":"Credit risk","C":"Liquidity risk","D":"Call risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Liquidity or marketability risk is the risk of not being able to purchase or sell a security easily.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-71","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"The second market is","choices":{"A":"listed securities trading OTC","B":"listed securities trading on an exchange","C":"institutional trading without using the services of a broker-dealer","D":"unlisted securities trading OTC"},"answer":"D","explanation":"D. unlisted securities trading OTC. The second market, not to be confused with the secondary market, is unlisted securities trading OTC (over-the-counter). The secondary market is broken down into the first market, the second market, the third market, and the fourth market. The first market is listed securities trading on an exchange, the third market is listed securities trading OTC, and the fourth market is institutional trading without using the services of a broker-dealer.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-72","section":"1 - Capital Markets","stem":"Income received from a limited partnership is considered","choices":{"A":"capital gains","B":"dividend income","C":"earned income","D":"passive income"},"answer":"D","explanation":"passive income. Income, losses, or gains from a partnership are passive. Passive income can only be offset by passive losses.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-73","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"All of the following are mandated or regulated under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 EXCEPT","choices":{"A":"the creation of the SEC","B":"market manipulation","C":"margin rules","D":"the full and fair disclosure required on new offerings"},"answer":"D","explanation":"D. the full and fair disclosure required on new offerings. The full and fair disclosure that's required on new offerings is covered under the Securities Act of 1933, not the Securities Exchange Act of 1934. The Securities Act of 1933 deals with the registration of new issues, and the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 deals with the trading of outstanding issues.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-74","section":"4 - Regulatory Framework","stem":"When a company files a registration statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) for registering new securities, which of the following must be included? I. the issuer's name and description of its business II. what the proceeds of sale will be used for III. financial statements IV. the company's capitalization","choices":{"A":"I and III","B":"I, II, and III","C":"I, III, and IV","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"D","explanation":"D, I, II, III, and IV. When a company files a registration statement with the SEC, it must include the issuer's name and description of its business, the names and addresses of all the company's control persons, what the proceeds will be used for, the company's capitalization, complete financial statements, any legal proceedings against the company, and so on.","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"},{"id":"yt-UDEMY-UDEMY3-75","section":"2 - Products & Risks","stem":"Common stockholders have which of the following rights and privileges? (I. The right to receive monthly audited financial reports  II. The right to vote for cash dividends  III. The right to vote for stock splits  IV. A residual claim to assets at dissolution)","choices":{"A":"I and II","B":"III and IV","C":"I, III, and IV","D":"II, III, and IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Common stockholders have a residual claim to the assets of the corporation at dissolution. Common stockholders are entitled to receive a report containing audited financial statements on a yearly — not monthly — basis. Stockholders vote on stock splits but do not vote to declare cash dividends (the board of directors declares dividends).","source":"YouTube/Udemy: Udemy Practice (UDEMYUDEMY3)"}];
